==English==

===Etymology===
From Latin ''[[directus]]'', past participle of ''[[dirigere]]'' ‘straighten, direct’, from ''[[di-]]'' + ''[[regere]]'' ‘make straight, rule’.

===Pronunciation===
*{{IPA|/dɪˈrɛkt/, /ˌdaɪˈrɛkt/, /dɚˈɛkt/}}
*{{SAMPA|/dI"rEkt/, /%daI"rEkt/, /d3`"Ekt/}}
*:Rhymes: [[Rhymes:English:-ɛkt|-ɛkt]]

===Adjective===
'''direct'''  ({{compar}}: '''more direct''', {{superl}}: '''most direct''')

# Straight, constant, without interruption.

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# To manage, control, steer.
# To aim at.
#:''They '''directed''' their fire towards the men on the wall.''
#:''He '''directed''' his question to the room in general.''

